[2] Cambodia
Date: Thu 21 Jul 2011
Source: The Phnom Penh Post [edited]
http://www.phnompenhpost.com/index.php/2011072150542/National-news/dengue-patients-hit-4600-this-year.html


With more than 4600 patients hospitalised from dengue so far this
year [2011] and outbreaks in 7 provinces, the National Dengue Control
Programme (NDCP) is calling for heightened vigilance during the
remainder of the rainy season, when the mosquito-borne disease is most
prevalent.

Parents should immediately take children suffering from a high fever
to the nearest health centre or hospital for treatment, NDCP director
Dr Ngan Chantha said yesterday [20 Jul 2011], explaining that early
and appropriate treatment was critical for preventing dengue
haemorrhagic fever, which can be fatal.

According to the NDCP, 4626 patients, primarily children, were
hospitalised in the 1st 27 weeks of this year [2011], compared to 2888
in the same period last year [2010]. 23 had died, compared to 9 in the
same period last year [2010]. The most serious outbreaks are in
Kampong Thom, Kampong Cham, Siem Reap, Kandal and Kampong Speu and
Banteay Meanchey provinces, Ngan Chantha said.

"The situation is not out of control," he said, noting that during
the 1st 27 weeks of 2009, almost 5200 patients had been hospitalized.

There remained, however, a possibility that the swiftly spreading
disease could spiral out of control if communities failed to eliminate
mosquito-breeding sites and individuals failed to protect themselves
from mosquito bites, he said.

The mosquito that transmits dengue bites during the day, so it is
necessary to keep napping infants under a mosquito net and for other
children (as well as adults) to wear long sleeve shirts, he said.

[Byline: Vincent Macisaac]

--
Communicated by:
PRO/MBDS

[According to the number of reported cases of dengue fever and dengue
hemorrhagic fever (DF/DHF) in the Western Pacific region, by country,
from WHO's Regional Office for the Western Pacific (WHO/WPRO), dated
19 Jul 2011 (available at
http://www.wpro.who.int/NR/rdonlyres/5A929C6D-00AC-4FDF-8D0F-1DE22039D5D5/0/19Jul2011.pdf),
there were 4626 cases and 23 deaths of dengue fever (DF) and dengue
hemorrhagic fever (DHF) in Cambodia in the 1st 27 week of 2011, with a
CFR (case fatality rate) of 0.50 percent. The trend of dengue
outbreaks has been increasing since April 2011; a total of 2888 cases
and 9 deaths due to dengue infection were reported in 2010 for the
same period, with a CFR 0.31 percent.

According to the newswire above, officials stated that there were
dengue outbreaks in 7 provinces of Cambodia in 2011. Although the
number of dengue cases in Cambodia in the 1st 27 weeks of 2011 (4626
cases) was higher than that of the same period in 2010 (2888 cases),
it was still lower than that of the same period in 2009 (5200 cases).

The total number of dengue fever cases in 2010 was 12 500 cases and
38 deaths, with a CFR of 0.30 percent (available at
http://www.wpro.who.int/internet/resources.ashx/MVP/WPR_D_91-10_Updated_2_May_2011.pdf).

For a map of Cambodia with provinces, see
http://www.discoveryindochina.com/cam/map_provinces.html. For the
interactive HealthMap/ProMED-mail map with links to other recent
PRO/MBDS and ProMED-mail postings on Cambodia and neighboring
countries, see http://healthmap.org/r/00N5. - Mod.SCM]

